The paper deals with coding techniques for the Grassmannian space, which is a mathematical object commonly used in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves algorithms and computational complexity, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) as likely sub-categories. The paper also mentions network coding, which falls under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper involves orders and representations of subspaces, which suggests cs.CC (Computational Complexity) as a possible sub-category.
